<subSubSection id="C3510DAA272EFF9EFF11FB36997FFE7C" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BF45E21272EFF9EFF11FB36995BFEA0" blockId="28.[120,1225,992,1767]" lastBlockId="29.[120,1226,225,1447]" lastPageId="29" lastPageNumber="30" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
DIAGNOSIS: (Asterisks in this section indicate traits exhibited by 
<taxonomicName id="4C4B25A2272EFF9FFC00FB379FA5FB11" authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1847" box="[953,1225,1216,1242]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dimidiata">
<emphasis id="B93F8233272EFF9FFC00FB379FA5FB11" box="[953,1225,1216,1242]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Monodelphis dimidiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that have yet to be confirmed for 
<taxonomicName id="4C4B25A2272EFF9FFDA7FB1099D2FACB" authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1842" box="[542,702,1255,1280]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphiops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="unistriata">
<emphasis id="B93F8233272EFF9FFDA7FB1099D2FACB" box="[542,702,1255,1280]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">M. unistriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.) Dorsal body pelage grayish middorsally, with (
<taxonomicName id="4C4B25A2272EFF9FFF79FAFB9A31FAEE" authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1842" box="[192,349,1292,1317]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphiops" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="unistriata">
<emphasis id="B93F8233272EFF9FFF79FAFB9A31FAEE" box="[192,349,1292,1317]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">M. unistriata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) or without (
<taxonomicName id="4C4B25A2272EFF9FFDBBFAFB99F1FAEE" authorityName="Wagner" authorityYear="1847" box="[514,669,1291,1317]" class="Mammalia" family="Didelphidae" genus="Monodelphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Didelphimorphia" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="dimidiata">
<emphasis id="B93F8233272EFF9FFDBBFAFB99F1FAEE" box="[514,669,1291,1317]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">M. dimidiata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) a single dark longitudinal stripe, contrasting with clear yellowish, orange, or reddish flanks; ventral pelage uniformly colored (yellowish, orangish, or reddish), without self-whitish markings. Mammae 6–5–6 = 17 to 11–5–11 = 27 (
<bibRefCitation id="EFDA23D0272EFF9FFF38FA8C9A11FA5D" author="Thomas, O." box="[129,381,1403,1430]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" refId="ref17523" refString="Thomas, O. 1888 b. Catalogue of the Marsupialia and Monotremata in the collection of the British Museum (Natural History). London: Trustees of the British Museum (Natural History)." type="book" year="1888">Thomas, 1888b: 361</bibRefCitation>
), including abdominal-inguinal and pectoral teats.* Thenar and first interdigital pads of hind foot separate*; hypothenar pad of hind foot absent.* Body pelage extends onto the tail to about the same extent dorsally and ventrally; tail scales arranged in spiral series. Infraorbital foramen dorsal to P3 or M1; frontal process of jugal present but rounded, not distinctly angular*; parietal usually (&gt; 90% of examined specimens) in contact with mastoid*; incisive foramina short; maxillopalatine fenestrae short; sphenorbital fissure usually large, exposing basisphenoid laterally*; infratemporal crest of alisphenoid distinct*; secondary foramen ovale usually absent (rarely present bilaterally)*; tympanic wing of alisphenoid usually small*; tip of anterior process of the malleus exposed or not on external surface of bulla*; rostral tympanic process of petrosal triangular (not broadly rounded), but sometimes concealing fenestra cochleae ventrally*; stapes columelliform, imperforate or microperforate*; subsquamosal foramen large*. Anterior cingulids of m2 and m3 broad; entoconids of m1–m3 distinct; dp3 small and incompletely molariform, with bicuspid trigonid and indistinct anterior cingulid*.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BF45E21272FFF9EFF11FE80997FFE7C" blockId="29.[120,1226,225,1447]" pageId="29" pageNumber="30">
